| alt1      = A large granite memorial, showing a list of names, among which is Josephine Butler
| caption1  = Butler's name on the lower section of the Reformers memorial, Kensal Green Cemetery
<!-- Image 2 -->
| image2    = Josephine BUTLER 1828-1906 Champion of Women's Rights lived here 1890-1893.jpg
| width2    = 
| alt2      = Circular blue plaque with the words "Josephine Butler / 1826–1906 / Champion of / Women's Rights / lived here / 1890–1893"
| caption2  = The [[blue plaque]] erected in 2001 by [[English Heritage]] at Butler's former residence in [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]]
}}

In 1907 Josephine Butler's name was added to the south side of the Reformers' Memorial in [[Kensal Green Cemetery]], London. The memorial was erected for those "who had defied custom and interest for the sake of conscience and public good".{{sfn|Crawford|2003|p=142}} She is celebrated in the [[Church of England]] with a [[Lesser Festival]] on 30 May,<ref name="CoE: 30 May" /> and represented in a [[stained glass]] window in Liverpool's [[Liverpool Cathedral|Anglican Cathedral]],{{sfn|Jordan|2001|p=297}} [[All Saints' Church, Cambridge]] and [[St Olave Hart Street|St Olave's Church]] in the [[City of London]].{{sfn|Beeson|2011|p=119}}

Her connections to Liverpool were memorialised in a more secular fashion. A building in the Faculty of Business and Law at [[Liverpool John Moores University]] was named "Josephine Butler House". The building, originally the first Radium Institute in the UK, in the Cultural Quarter in [[Hope Street, Liverpool|Hope Street]], was built in 1867 and demolished in 2013 when the site became a car park<ref name="LDE: LMU" /><ref name="DP: LMU" /> and subsequently student housing which opened in 2015.<ref name="BD: LMU" />

In 1915 the LNA merged with the International Abolitionist Federation to form the Association of Moral and Social Hygiene, which changed its name to the Josephine Butler Society in 1953. As at 2017 the society still operates; it campaigns for the protection of prostitutes and provides "protection for women and children who are criminally detained, violently abused or exploited by others who profit from their prostitution".{{sfn|Daggers|Neal|2006|p=3}}<ref name="JBS: Principles" />

In 2005 [[Durham University]] named [[Josephine Butler College, Durham|Josephine Butler College]] after her, reflecting her and George's connection to the area and the university.<ref name="DU: College" /><ref name="DU: Butler coll" /> The [[Women's Library]], at the [[London School of Economics]], holds a number of collections related to Butler. They include papers from the Ladies' National Association; more than 2,500 letters in the Josephine Butler Letter Collection; and the Josephine Butler Society Library consisting of books and pamphlets collected by the society.<ref name="LSE: Library" /> In 2001 [[English Heritage]] placed a [[blue plaque]] on her former residence in Wimbledon;<ref name="EH: London plaque" /> her former house in Cheltenham was demolished in the 1970s, but in 2002 the Cheltenham Civic Society placed a plaque on the building which now occupies the site.<ref name="GE: Plaque" />

Butler was not only [[Christian feminism|a staunch feminist but a passionate Christian]],{{sfn|Summers|1999|pp=8–9}} whose favourite phrase was "God and one woman make a majority".{{sfn|Mathers|2014|p=109}} Although staunchly liberal, she felt constant tensions between her liberal and feminist philosophies. According to the feminist historian [[Barbara Caine]], "Liberalism provided the framework for Butler's whole social and political approach. It was an integral part of her feminism", although it was in conflict with the liberal approach to sexuality and desire. Butler resolved the conflict through her religion.{{sfn|Caine|1993|pp=155–56}}

According to Walkowitz, Butler "pushed liberal feminism in new directions, developing theories and methods of political agitation that directly affected future campaigns for the emancipation of women".{{sfn|Walkowitz|2004}} She developed new approaches to campaigning and moved the debate beyond discussions in middle-class houses to the public forum, bringing into the political debate women who had never been involved before.{{sfn|Walkowitz|2004}}<ref name="Guard: Heroine" /> Butler's campaigning, says Walkowitz, "not only reshaped gender, class, and sexual subjectivities in late Victorian Britain but also informed national political history and state-building".{{sfn|Walkowitz|2004}}

Numerous historians consider the success of the campaign to repeal the Contagious Diseases Acts to be a milestone in the [[History of feminism|history of female emancipation]].{{sfn|Walkowitz|2004}} According to the political historian Margaret Hamilton, the campaign showed that "attitudes toward women were changing".{{sfn|Hamilton|1978|p=14}} The feminist scholar [[Sheila Jeffreys]] says that Butler is "one of the bravest and most imaginative feminists in history",<ref name="Guard: Heroine" /> while Fawcett wrote that she was "convinced that&nbsp;... [Butler] should take the rank of the most distinguished Englishwoman of the nineteenth century".{{sfn|Fawcett|Turner|1927|p=1}} Her unnamed obituarist in ''The Daily News'' considered that Butler's name

{{quote|will always rank amongst the noblest of the social reformers, the fruit of whose labours is the highest inheritance that we have. She fought with enormous courage and self-sacrifice in a battlefield where she was subjected to the fiercest antagonism&nbsp;... She never faltered in her task, and it is to her in supreme that the English statute book owes the removal of one of the greatest blots that ever defaced it. Her victory marked one of the great stages of progress of woman to that equality of treatment which is the final test of a nation's civilization.<ref name="DN: Obit" />}}

